Stock Market News Sentiment Analysis

Problem Statement

Business Context

Stock prices on exchanges like NASDAQ don't just move because of numbersthey're hugely affected by a company's earnings, cool new inventions, partnerships, and overall market mood. News articles and social media can flip investor feelings overnight, making prices jump or crash in this super competitive finance world. With tons of news coming from everywhere, it's hard for investors and analysts to keep up and figure out what actually matters, so firms need smart tools to read the sentiment and plug it into their strategies.

Problem Definition

An investment startup gave me a dataset of daily news articles for one specific NASDAQ company, plus its daily stock prices and trading volumes. As part of their Data Science team, I built an AI system to:

Automatically scan and analyze news to score sentiment (positive, negative, neutral).

Group it into weekly summaries to smooth out daily noise.

Connect those insights to stock movements for better price predictions.

Data Dictionary

  • date : The date the news was released
  • news : The content of news articles that could potentially affect the company's stock price
  • open : The stock price (in $) at the beginning of the day
  • high : The highest stock price (in $) reached during the day
  • low : The lowest stock price (in $) reached during the day
  • close : The adjusted stock price (in $) at the end of the day
  • volume : The number of shares traded during the day
  • label : The sentiment polarity of the news content
    • 1: positive
    • 0: neutral
    • -1: negative

def start_timer() -> float:
    """
    Start a timer
    """
    return time.time()


def get_time(start_time_float: float) -> str:
    diff = abs(time.time() - start_time_float)
    hours, remainder = divmod(diff, SECS_IN_MIN*SECS_IN_MIN)
    minutes, seconds = divmod(remainder, SECS_IN_MIN)
    fractional_seconds = seconds - int(seconds)

    ms = fractional_seconds * MSEC
    return f"{int(minutes)}m {int(seconds)}s {int(ms)}ms"


def show_timer(start_time_float: float) -> None:
    print(f"\nRun Time: {get_time(start_time_float)}")


def show_banner(title: str, section: str='') -> None:
    """
    Prints a stylized banner for notebook readability, adjusted to remove
    the trailing hash symbol on the bottom line.

    +-------------------------------------+
    |                                     |
    +-------------------------------------+
    """

    PADDING = 2
    strlen = len(title) + PADDING
    line = '+-' + '-' * strlen + '-+'

    # Top Line
    print('')
    print(line)

    # Show Title
    print('|  ' + title.upper() + '  |')

    # Bottom Line
    print(line)

    # Show section (if provided)
    if section:
        print('| ' + section)

    print('') # Final newline for spacing

# Define label barchart
def labeled_barchart(df: pd.DataFrame, feature: str, perc: bool=False, n=None) -> None:
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    df: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count default False
    n: displays the top n category levels default None
    """
    total = len(df[feature])
    count = df[feature].nunique()

    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 5))  # Set the figure size

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)

    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=df,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=df[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(100 * p.get_height() / total)

        else:
            label = p.get_height()
            x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2
            y = p.get_height()

            ax.annotate(
                label,
                (x, y),
                ha="center",
                va="center",
                size=12,
                xytext=(0, 5),
                textcoords="offset points",
          )

    plt.show()

def distribution_plot_wrt_target(data: pd.DataFrame, predictor: str, target: str) -> None:
    """
    Plots the distribution of a predictor variable with respect to a target variable.
    This function is robust and works for binary or multi-class targets.
    """
    # Set a clean and professional style
    plt.style.use('seaborn-v0_8-whitegrid')
    fig, axs = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(20, 6)) # Changed to a 1x3 layout

    # --- Plot 1: Overlaid Histogram for all classes ---
    axs[0].set_title(f'Distribution of {predictor.title()} by {target.title()}', fontsize=14, fontweight='bold')
    sns.histplot(
        data=data,
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0],
        hue=target, # Use hue to automatically separate classes
        palette='viridis', # A vibrant and clear color palette
        element='step' # Use steps for clearer overlap
    )
    axs[0].legend(title=target.title(), labels=data[target].unique())

    # --- Plot 2: Boxplot with outliers ---
    axs[1].set_title(f'Boxplot of {predictor.title()} by {target.title()}', fontsize=14, fontweight='bold')
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=target, y=predictor, ax=axs[1], palette='magma'
    )

    # --- Plot 3: Boxplot without outliers ---
    axs[2].set_title(f'Boxplot of {predictor.title()} (No Outliers)', fontsize=14, fontweight='bold')
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data,
        x=target,
        y=predictor,
        ax=axs[2],
        showfliers=False, # Hide outliers for a clearer view of the distribution
        palette='plasma'
    )

    # --- Final Touches ---
    plt.tight_layout(pad=2.0)
    plt.show()

# Define plot distributions
def distribution_plot_wrt_target_old(df: pd.DataFrame, predictor: pd.DataFrame, target: str) -> None:
  fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(12, 10))
  target_unique = df[target].unique()

  axs[0,0].set_title('Distribution of target for target=' + str(target))
  sns.histplot(
      data=df[df[target] == target_unique[0]],
      x=predictor,
      kde=True,
      ax=axs[0, 0],
      color='teal',
  )

  axs[0, 1].set_title('Distribution of target for target=' + str(target))
  sns.histplot(
      data=df[df[target] == target_unique[1]],
      x=predictor,
      kde=True,
      ax=axs[0, 1],
      color='orange',
  )

  axs[1, 0].set_title('Boxplot w/ respect to target=' + str(target))
  sns.boxplot(data=df, x=target, y=predictor, ax=axs[1,0], palette='gist_rainbow')

  axs[1, 1].set_title('Boxplot (w/o outliers) w/ respect to target')
  sns.boxplot(
      data=df,
      x=target,
      y=predictor,
      ax=axs[1, 1],
      showfliers=False,
      palette='gist_rainbow',
  )

  plt.tight_layout()
  plt.show()

def histogram_boxplot(
    df: pd.DataFrame,
    feature: str,
    figsize: Tuple=(14, 8),
    kde: bool = True,
    bins=None,
    style: str='seaborn-v0_8-whitegrid',
) -> None:
    """
    Enhanced boxplot and histogram combined for aesthetic appeal.

    df: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (14, 8))
    kde: whether to the show density curve (default True)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    style: matplotlib style to use (default 'seaborn-v0_8-whitegrid')
    """

    # --- Set the Plot Style ---
    plt.style.use(style)

    # --- Create Subplots and Define Layout ---
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid = 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )

    # --- Add a Main Title ---
    f2.suptitle(
        f"Distribution of {feature.title()} with Boxplot and Histogram",
        fontsize=16,
        fontweight='bold',
        color='#333333' # Dark gray title color
    )

    # --- Boxplot (ax_box2) ---
    box_color = "#1f77b4"  # A nice deep blue
    sns.boxplot(
        data=df,
        x=feature,
        ax=ax_box2,
        showmeans=True,
        color=box_color,
        meanprops={
            "marker": "o",
            "markerfacecolor": "white",
            "markeredgecolor": "red",
            "markersize": "8",
        },
        linewidth=1.5,
    )
    # Remove x-label from boxplot for cleaner look
    ax_box2.set_xlabel("")
    # Add minor grid lines for subtle detail
    ax_box2.grid(True, which='both', linestyle='--', linewidth=0.5, alpha=0.7)

    # --- Histogram (ax_hist2) ---
    hist_color = "#2ca02c" # A complimentary green
    # Select the appropriate histplot based on whether bins are specified
    if bins:
        sns.histplot(
            data=df, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, color=hist_color
        )
    else:
        sns.histplot(
            data=df, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, color=hist_color
        )

    # --- Add Mean and Median Lines with Enhancements ---
    mean_val = df[feature].mean()
    median_val = df[feature].median()

    # Mean line (dashed, vibrant red)
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        mean_val,
        color="#d62728",
        linestyle="--",
        linewidth=2.5,
        label=f"Mean: {mean_val:,.2f}",
    )

    # Median line (solid, dark orange)
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        median_val,
        color="#ff7f0e",
        linestyle="-",
        linewidth=2.5,
        label=f"Median: {median_val:,.2f}",
    )

    # Add Legend and Other Details ---
    ax_hist2.legend(loc='upper right', frameon=True, shadow=True, fancybox=True)
    ax_hist2.set_ylabel("Frequency / Count", fontsize=12)
    ax_hist2.set_xlabel(feature.title(), fontsize=12)

    # Add minor grid lines for subtle detail
    ax_hist2.grid(True, which='both', linestyle='--', linewidth=0.5, alpha=0.7)

    # Tight layout adjustment
    f2.tight_layout(rect=[0, 0, 1, 0.96]) # Adjust for suptitle

    # --- Optional: Display the figure ---
    plt.show()

# You would typically call this function after defining it, e.g.:
# # Assuming df is your DataFrame and 'Age' is the column:

def plot_word_count_distribution(
    data: pd.DataFrame,
    word_count_column: str,
) -> None:
    """
    Enhanced histogram for visualizing the distribution of word counts.

    data: dataframe
    word_count_column: the column containing word counts (e.g., 'word_count')
    figsize: size of figure (default (12, 7))
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default 50 for more detail)
    style: matplotlib style to use (default 'seaborn-v0_8-darkgrid')
    color: color of the histogram bars
    """

    # --- Set the Plot Style ---
    plt.style.use('seaborn-v0_8-darkgrid')

    # Calculate key statistics for annotation
    counts = data[word_count_column].dropna()
    mean_val = counts.mean()
    median_val = counts.median()

    # --- Create the Figure and Axes ---
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 7))

    # --- Plot the Histogram ---
    sns.histplot(
        counts,
        bins=50,
        color='#3A5A40',
        edgecolor='#2a2a2a', # Dark edge for contrast
        kde=True,            # Add a Kernel Density Estimate for smoothness
        linewidth=0.8,
        line_kws={
            'color': '#A3B18A',
            'linewidth': 3,
            'alpha': 0.8
        } # Lighter line for KDE
    )

    # --- Add Mean and Median Lines ---
    # Mean line (dashed, bright red)
    plt.axvline(
        mean_val,
        color='#d62728',
        linestyle='--',
        linewidth=2.5,
        label=f"Mean: {mean_val:,.2f}"
    )

    # Median line (dotted, dark orange)
    plt.axvline(
        median_val,
        color='#ff7f0e',
        linestyle=':',
        linewidth=2.5,
        label=f"Median: {median_val:,.2f}"
    )

    # --- Add Title and Labels ---
    column_str = word_count_column.replace('_', ' ').title()
    plt.title(
        f"Distribution of {column_str}",
        fontsize=18,
        fontweight='bold',
        pad=15 # Padding above the chart
    )
    plt.xlabel(column_str, fontsize=14, labelpad=10)
    plt.ylabel('Frequency', fontsize=14, labelpad=10)

    # --- Add Legend and Final Touches ---
    plt.legend(loc='upper right', frameon=True, shadow=True, fancybox=True)

    # Remove top and right spines for a cleaner look
    sns.despine(trim=True)

def show_plot_stock_price(df: pd.DataFrame) -> None:
    # --- Enhanced Box Plotting ---

    fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(14, 12))
    fig.suptitle('Distribution of Stock Prices by News Sentiment', fontsize=16, y=1.02)
    axes = axes.flatten()

    price_variables = ['open', 'high', 'low', 'close']

    for i, variable in enumerate(price_variables):
        variable_title = variable.title()
        sns.boxplot(
            data=df,
            x="label_text",
            y=variable,
            ax=axes[i],
            palette='viridis',

        axes[i].set_xlabel('News Sentiment', fontsize=12)
        axes[i].set_ylabel(f'Price ({variable_title})', fontsize=12)

    plt.tight_layout(pad=3.0)
    plt.savefig('stock_price_boxplots_enhanced.png')

# Plot top words
def plot_top_word_freq() -> None:

    """
    Enhanced horizontal bar chart for visualizing the Top N most frequent words.

    words: list of all words (must correspond to word_counts)
    word_counts: list of all word frequencies (must correspond to words)
    top_n: Number of top words to display (default 20)
    figsize: size of figure (default (12, 8))
    style: matplotlib style to use (default 'seaborn-v0_8-white')
    palette: color palette to use (default 'viridis_r' - reversed viridis)
    """

    style = 'seaborn-v0_8-white',
    palette = 'viridis_r'

    # --- Prepare Data and Set Style ---
    plt.style.use(style)

    # Combine into a DataFrame for easy sorting and handling
    df_words = pd.DataFrame({
        'Word': words,
        'Frequency': word_counts
    }).sort_values(by='Frequency', ascending=False).head(COMMON_WORD_CNT)

    # --- Create the Figure ---
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))

    # --- Plot the Bar Chart using Seaborn ---
    # Using barplot with order ensures bars are consistently sorted
    ax = sns.barplot(
        x='Frequency',
        y='Word',
        data=df_words,
        palette=palette,
        edgecolor='#333333',
        linewidth=0.5
    )

    # --- Add Data Labels (The "Bells & Whistles") ---
    for p in ax.patches:

        # Get the width of the bar (frequency value)
        width = p.get_width()

        # Place the label slightly after the end of the bar
        ax.annotate(
            f'{int(width):,}', # Format the count with commas
            (width, p.get_y() + p.get_height() / 2.),
            ha='left',
            va='center',
            xytext=(5, 0),  # 5 points horizontal offset
            textcoords='offset points',
            fontsize=11,
            color='black',
            fontweight='bold'
        )

    # --- Enhance Title and Labels ---
    plt.title(
        f"Top {COMMON_WORD_CNT} Most Frequent Words",
        fontsize=18,
        fontweight='bold',
        pad=15
    )
    plt.xlabel("Word Frequency", fontsize=14, labelpad=10)
    plt.ylabel("Word", fontsize=14, labelpad=10)

    # --- Final Touches ---
    # Customize the x-axis ticks to be integers
    max_freq = df_words['Frequency'].max()
    ax.set_xticks(ax.get_xticks()) # Keep current ticks
    ax.set_xticklabels([f'{int(x):,}' for x in ax.get_xticks()]) # Format ticks

    # Remove the surrounding frame (spines) for a cleaner look
    sns.despine(left=True, bottom=True)

    # Add a subtle grid on the x-axis
    ax.grid(axis='x', linestyle='--', alpha=0.6)

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

# Remove special chars
def remove_special_chars(text: str) -> str:
    pattern = '[^A-Za-z0-9]+'
    text = ''.join(re.sub(pattern,' ', text))

    return text
In[50]:
# Remove stop words
def remove_stopwords(text: str) -> str:
    # split text into separate words
    words = text.split()

    # remove English language stopwords
    new_text = ' '.join([word for word in words if word not in stopwords.words('english')])

    return new_text
In[51]:
def apply_porter_stemmer(text: str) -> str:
    words = text.split()
    new_text = ' '.join([ps.stem(word) for word in words])

    return new_text

# INDEPENDENT VARIABLES aka features
features_df = X = data['final_clean_text']

# DEPENDENT VARIABLE aka target
target_df = y = data['label']

x_training_data = None
y_training_data = None
x_temp_data = None
y_temp_data = None

x_validation_data = None
y_validation_data = None
x_testing_data = None
y_testing_data = None

# Split data into 80% train, 20% temporary (to be split into validation & test)
x_training_data, x_temp_data, y_training_data, y_temp_data = train_test_split(
    features_df,
    target_df,
    test_size=TEMPORARY_DATA_SPLIT,
    stratify=target_df,
    random_state=SEED
)

# Further split temporary set into 10% validation, 10% test
x_validation_data, x_testing_data, y_validation_data, y_testing_data = train_test_split(
    x_temp_data,
    y_temp_data,
    test_size=HALF_DATA_SPLIT,
    stratify=y_temp_data,
    random_state=SEED
)

    return ['Feature ' + str(i) for i in range(vector_size)]
In[235]:
# Calculates the average vector value of a document list regardless of embedding type.
def calculate_mean_word_vectors(doc: str, word_vector_dict: dict, vocab: set, vector_size: int) -> np.ndarray:

    # Initialize a randomized list with noise to store word vectors, use the Generator's uniform method.
    rng = np.random.default_rng(SEED)
    feature_vector = rng.uniform(-0.01, 0.01, vector_size)

    # It splits the document into words and keeps only the words that exist in
    # the trained model's vocabulary
    doc_list = [word for word in doc.split() if word in vocab]

    # Calculate the average vector value of the words in the document that
    # are also in the vocabulary dataset.
    if doc_list:
        feature_vector = np.mean([word_vector_dict[word] for word in doc_list], axis=0)

    return feature_vector
In[72]:
def encode_embeddings(
    x_training: pd.DataFrame,
    x_validation: pd.DataFrame,
    x_testing: pd.DataFrame,
    word_vector_dict: dict,
    vocab: set,
    vector_size: int,
    vector_cols: list
) -> Tuple[np.ndarray, np.ndarray, np.ndarray]:

    # --- Define the Nested Wrapper Function ---
    # This function is defined inside encode_embeddings, allowing it to "see"
    # all the input arguments (word_vector_dict, vocabulary, vector_size).
    # It only accepts the 'doc' string passed by the .apply() method.
    def vectorizer(doc: str):
        return calculate_mean_word_vectors(
            doc,
            word_vector_dict,
            vocab,
            vector_size
        )

    x_training_data_emb = pd.DataFrame(
        pd.Series(x_training).apply(vectorizer).tolist(),
        columns=vector_cols
    )

    x_validation_data_emb = pd.DataFrame(
        pd.Series(x_validation).apply(vectorizer).tolist(),
        columns=vector_cols
    )

    x_testing_data_emb = pd.DataFrame(
        pd.Series(x_testing).apply(vectorizer).tolist(),
        columns=vector_cols
    )

    return x_training_data_emb, x_validation_data_emb, x_testing_data_emb

# Define Plot Confusion Matrix
def plot_confusion_matrix(mod: RandomForestClassifier, predictors: pd.DataFrame, target: str, title: str='Confusion Matrix') -> None:
    """
    Plots a confusion matrix to visualize the performance of a classification model.

    Parameters:
    model (classifier): Trained model used for prediction.
    predictors (array-like): Feature set used for making predictions.
    target (array-like): True labels corresponding to predictors.
    title (str, optional): Title for the plot. The default is 'Confusion Matrix'.

    Returns:
    None: Displays the confusion matrix plot.
    """

    # Generate predictions
    pred = mod.predict(predictors)

    # Compute confusion matrix
    cm = confusion_matrix(target, pred)

    # Get unique class labels from the target data
    labels = np.unique(target)
    labels_str = [LABEL_SENTIMENT[label] for label in labels]

    # Create a heatmap
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 5))
    sns.heatmap(
        cm, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='Blues',
        xticklabels=labels_str, yticklabels=labels_str
    )

    # Set labels and title
    plt.xlabel('Predicted Labels')
    plt.ylabel('Actual Labels')
    plt.title(f'{title}') # Title of the plot.

    # Show plot
    plt.show()

# Define Model Performance Classification SKLearn
def model_performance_classification_sklearn(mod: RandomForestClassifier, predictors: pd.DataFrame, target: str) -> pd.DataFrame:
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check classification model performance.

    Parameters:
    - model: Trained classification model
    - predictors: Independent variables (features)
    - target: Dependent variable (true labels)

    Returns:
    - DataFrame with Accuracy, Recall, Precision, and F1-score.
    """

    # Predicting using the independent variables.
    pred = mod.predict(predictors)

    # Compute classification metrics
    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)
    recall = recall_score(target, pred, average='weighted')  # Use 'binary' if binary classification
    precision = precision_score(target, pred, average='weighted')
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred, average='weighted')

    # Creating a dataframe of metrics.
    data_perf = pd.DataFrame({
        'Accuracy': [acc],
        'Recall': [recall],
        'Precision': [precision],
        'F1': [f1],
    })

    return data_perf

You want scores >= 75.0 or higher with a gap less than <= 5.0%

Use F1 Score for calculations.

Why F1? The F1-Score is the harmonic mean of Precision and Recall. It is the best single indicator of a model's overall performance because it punishes models that achieve high scores by gaming the system (e.g., guessing the majority class to get high Accuracy, or guessing Positive constantly to get high Recall).

In[114]:
# ==================================
#  OVERFITTING
# ==================================
#
#  The Overfitting Scenario (Large Gap, High Training Score)
# Small Gap, High Scores
# Overfitting -> Training:98%, Validation:80%, Gap:18%
# This is where the model fails to generalize. The gap is the immediate giveaway.
# Decrease complexity!

# ==================================
#  UNDERFITTING
# ==================================
#
#  The Underfitting Scenario (Small Gap, Low Scores)
# Small Gap, Low Scores
# Underfitting-> Training:55% Validation:53% Gap:2%
# In this case, the model is too simple to capture the complexity of the data. It's generalizing well (the gap is small), but it's generalizing poorly learned patterns.
# Increase complexity (e.g., try a more powerful algorithm like a Gradient Boosted Tree, add more features).
#
def check_fitting(training_df: pd.DataFrame, validation_df: pd.DataFrame) -> str:
    """
    Checks for underfitting, overfitting, or good fit based on F1 scores.

    train_f1: F1-Score on the training data (e.g., 0.95)
    val_f1: F1-Score on the validation data (e.g., 0.80)
    gap_threshold: Maximum acceptable absolute difference (e.g., 0.05 or 5%)
    score_threshold: Minimum acceptable absolute score for good performance (e.g., 0.70 or 70%)
    """
    training_f1 = training_df['F1'][0]
    validation_f1 = validation_df['F1'][0]
    gap = abs(training_f1 - validation_f1)

    print(f'\nGap: {gap}')

    #  The Overfitting Scenario (Large Gap, High Training Score)
    if gap >= FITTING_GAP_THRESH:

        # Case 1: Gap >= 5% Scores < 75%
        if training_f1 < FITTING_SCORE_THRESH and validation_f1 < FITTING_SCORE_THRESH:
            print(f'Message: The model is too complex (high variance), but its absolute performance is also low. Action: Drastically increase regularization/simplify the model.')

        # Case 2: Gap >= 5% Scores >= 75%
        if training_f1 >= FITTING_SCORE_THRESH and validation_f1 >= FITTING_SCORE_THRESH:
            print('Message: Severe Overfitting. The model is performing well on training data but poorly on validation data. Action: Decrease complexity (e.g., increase regularization/reduce features) until the gap closes.')

        return 'overfitting'

    #  The Underfitting Scenario (Small Gap, Low Scores)
    if gap < FITTING_GAP_THRESH:
        # Case 3:
        if training_f1 < FITTING_SCORE_THRESH and validation_f1 < FITTING_SCORE_THRESH:
            print('Message: The model is too simple (high bias) and can\'t capture the data patterns. Action: Increase complexity (e.g., try a more powerful algorithm, add features) to push scores higher.')

        return 'underfitting'

    # Case 4: Gap < 5% and scores >= 75%
    # The model generalizes well and meets the performance goal. Action: Select this model for final testing.
    return 'fit'

def tune_model(
    mod: RandomForestClassifier,
    x_training_data: pd.DataFrame,
    y_training_data: pd.DataFrame,
    tuned_title=''
) -> RandomForestClassifier:

    start_time = start_timer()
    show_banner(f'Tuning {tuned_title} Model')

    # Defined globally or passed into the function scope
    parameters = {
        # Force simplicity: max_depth cannot be high
        "max_depth": [3, 4, 5, 6],

        # Increase min_samples_leaf aggressively (fights overfitting)
        "min_samples_leaf": randint(20, 60),

        # Increase min_samples_split aggressively (fights overfitting)
        "min_samples_split": randint(40, 100),

        # Keeping n_estimators fixed or slightly varied for stability
        "n_estimators": [300, 500, 700],

        # Keep max_features conservative
        "max_features": ["sqrt", 0.4]
    }

    # Use the aggressive parameter distribution
    random_search = RandomizedSearchCV(
        estimator=mod,
        param_distributions=parameters, # <-- Using the aggressive space
        n_iter=CV_RANDOM_SEARCH_CNT,
        scoring='f1_weighted',
        cv=StratifiedKFold(
            CV_FOLDS,
            shuffle=True,
            random_state=SEED
        ),
        n_jobs=USE_ALL_PROCS,
        random_state=SEED
    )

    random_search.fit(x_training_data, y_training_data)

    print('Best parameters found: ', random_search.best_params_)
    print('Best CV F1-weighted Score: ', random_search.best_score_)

    # Get the best model
    best_rf = random_search.best_estimator_

    # Re-fit on the full training set (optional, but good practice before prediction)
    best_rf.fit(x_training_data, y_training_data)

    show_timer(start_time) # Placeholder for timer

    # NOTE: The return type is RandomForestClassifier (the best model), not RandomizedSearchCV
    return best_rf

def rf_tuned_model() -> RandomForestClassifier:
    return RandomForestClassifier(
        max_depth=4,             # Good controlled depth
        min_samples_leaf=40,     # Strong pruning to prevent initial severe overfitting
        min_samples_split=80,    # Strong split guardrail
        n_estimators=500,
        max_features='sqrt',
        random_state=SEED
    )

# Dynamically Pick Winner By Score
def get_best_model(validation_data: pd.DataFrame) -> dict:

    # Analyze the validation data
    # Assuming that there is no over & under fitting, pick the model with the
    # Highest validation F1 score regardless of base/tuned modeling

    # Extract the F1 row using .loc[]
    # This returns a Pandas Series where the index labels are the model names/columns
    f1_scores_series = model_validation_comparison_data.loc['F1']

    # Find the highest F1-score value
    highest_f1_score = f1_scores_series.max()

    # Find the index (model name) corresponding to that highest value
    best_model_title = f1_scores_series.idxmax()

    # Get the index of the winning model's title
    best_model_index = model_titles.index(best_model_title)

    # Retrieve the actual trained classifier model
    best_model = models[best_model_index]

    # Select the corresponding predictor data for testing
    best_predictor = model_predictors[best_model_index]

    return {
        'highest_f1_score': highest_f1_score,
        'best_model_index': best_model_index,
        'best_model_title': best_model_title,
        'best_model': best_model,
        'best_predictor': best_predictor
    }

Summarization

Note:

  • The model is expected to summarize the news from the week by identifying the top three positive and negative events that are most likely to impact the price of the stock.

  • As an output, the model is expected to return a JSON containing two keys, one for Positive Events and one for Negative Events.

For the project, we need to define the prompt to be fed to the LLM to help it understand the task to perform. The following should be the components of the prompt:

  1. Role: Specifies the role the LLM will be taking up to perform the specified task, along with any specific details regarding the role
  • Example: You are an expert data analyst specializing in news content analysis.
  1. Task: Specifies the task to be performed and outlines what needs to be accomplished, clearly defining the objective
  • Example: Analyze the provided news headline and return the main topics contained within it.
  1. Instructions: Provides detailed guidelines on how to perform the task, which includes steps, rules, and criteria to ensure the task is executed correctly
  • Example:
Instructions:
1. Read the news headline carefully.
2. Identify the main subjects or entities mentioned in the headline.
3. Determine the key events or actions described in the headline.
4. Extract relevant keywords that represent the topics.
5. List the topics in a concise manner.
  1. Output Format: Specifies the format in which the final response should be structured, ensuring consistency and clarity in the generated output
  • Example: Return the output in JSON format with keys as the topic number and values as the actual topic.

Full Prompt Example:

You are an expert data analyst specializing in news content analysis.

Task: Analyze the provided news headline and return the main topics contained within it.

Instructions:
1. Read the news headline carefully.
2. Identify the main subjects or entities mentioned in the headline.
3. Determine the key events or actions described in the headline.
4. Extract relevant keywords that represent the topics.
5. List the topics in a concise manner.

Return the output in JSON format with keys as the topic number and values as the actual topic.

Sample Output:

{"1": "Politics", "2": "Economy", "3": "Health" }

# Defining a function to parse the JSON output from the model
def extract_json_data(json_str: str) -> dict:

    NOT_FOUND = -1
    json_data = {}

    try:
        # Find the indices of the opening and closing curly braces
        json_start = json_str.find('{')
        json_end = json_str.rfind('}')

        if json_start != NOT_FOUND and json_end != NOT_FOUND:
            extracted_category = json_str[json_start:json_end + 1]  # Extract the JSON object
            json_data = json.loads(extracted_category)

    except json.JSONDecodeError as e:
        print(f"Error parsing JSON: {e}")

    return json_data

def filter_response(resp: str) -> str:
    """
    Sometimes the llama response will include greetings EVEN if told not to. To
    add extra security we will manually filter it out.
    """

    filter_strings = [
        'Here is the valid JSON output for the given news headlines:',
    ]

    for filter_str in filter_strings:
        if filter_str in resp:
            resp = resp.replace(filter_str, '').strip()

    return resp.strip()

prompt = """
Role: You are an expert financial analyst specializing in stock market news analysis.

### **Task:**
Given a set of **news headlines**, extract **positive** and **negative** financial events that could impact stock prices.

### **Instructions:**
1. **Analyze each news headline carefully.**
2. **Identify the company, industry, or entity mentioned.**
3. **Determine the key event or action** (e.g., earnings report, product launch, legal trouble).
4. **Assess the likely impact** on stock prices:
   - **Positive News:** Events likely to **increase** stock prices.
   - **Negative News:** Events likely to **decrease** stock prices.
5. **STRICT OUTPUT FORMAT:**
   - Return **ONLY** a **valid JSON object**.
   - **DO NOT** include any introductory text, explanations, greetings, small talk or comments!
   - The output must **begin and end with `{}`** and follow valid JSON syntax.
   - Any deviation from this format is considered incorrect.

### **Output Format (STRICTLY ENFORCED, NO EXTRA TEXT)**:
```json
{
  "Positive News": [ "List of positive events extracted from headlines" ],
  "Negative News": [ "List of negative events extracted from headlines" ]
}
"""

def get_mistral_response(prompt: str, news: str) -> str:
    """
    Mistral v1 AI Model
    This function is designed to interact with a large language model (LLM) named Mistral,
    specifically version 1, sending it a prompt and relevant news articles, and then
    processing the model's response. It aims to return a JSON object extracted from
    the model's output.
    """

    prompt_str = f"""[INST]{prompt}News Articles: {news}[/INST]"""

    llm_resp = llm(
        prompt_str, # Prompt to send to the LlaMa
        max_tokens=200,   # Controls max response length
        temperature=0.5,  # Slight randomness for varied responses
        top_p=0.95,  # Nucleus sampling
        top_k=50,    # Limits vocabulary choice
        echo=False,
    )

    resp = llm_resp['choices'][0]['text']

    if not resp:
        print(f'Warning: News article of {len(news)} characters produced no output!')
        return ''

    return filter_response(resp.strip())

Conclusions and Recommendations

We used an LLM to do miltiple tasks, one stage at a time. What was found was:

  • The final Testing F1 score of 0.384864 is a robust measure of the model's performance.

  • The drop from the Validation F1 (0.4463) to the Testing F1 (0.384864) is typical and expected. It confirms that the Validation score was a good, slightly optimistic estimate of performance, and your model did not overfit the Validation set.

  • We first identified the overall sentiment of the news articles.

  • The articles were very long in character count/length and parsed by keywords.

  • Next we identify keywords that point to specific sentiment apart from the overall article.

  • We then test the text and compare it to others to get the oeverall sentiment to determine which category it belongs do.

  • Last we count all the labels/sentiment to determine how much positive/negative/neutral info is available to make a descison on investing.

  • The dates also play a important factor as it tells when the news happened and if the issue is ongoing or not.

  • There was negative and positive news in the same article at times.

  • Some negative news didn't drop the price as well as some positive news didn't raise the price.

  • Prompting needs specific instructions to get the results that you want.
